The mode of growth of Roman law and the ‘relation between directa Aquilia and utilis Aquilia may be illustrated by similar phenomena in English law, and the relation between the two forms of action called Trespass and Trespass on the Oase, Trespass, which lies for injury to real or personal property or to the person, accom- panied with violence, has a more extensive application than directa Aquilia, but viewed only as redrossing injurios to personal property, is nearly coextensive in its range. The original scheme of actions, devised in comparatively barbarous times, contained no remedy for injurios where there is no act done but only a culpable omission, or where the actis not immediately injurious, but only by conse· quence or collaterally, or where the idea of force is inapplicable because the subject-matter is not corporeal or tangible, although the injury may be by act direct and immediate in its operation. Accordingly, anew writ of Trespass on the Osse was framed upon the analogy of the old torm of Trespass (confer, ad exemplum institorias, ς 162, comm), applying to cases where the injury is not immediate, or the subject affected is not corporeal, or the agency is not bodily force. What Edward Ι directed to be done by the clerks in chanaam, and what was done by the introduction of the action of lltespass on the (lese, was exaotly analogous to what the praetore did when, in virtue of their magisteria] authority, they supplemented the civil law by the introduction of actiones ficticiae and actiones in factum.
